article.description: Raul Lopez had 13 points and 10 assists off the bench to lead the Jazz past the 76ers 106-97 Monday night.
article.headline: Utah's Harpring scores 19 points
article.linkText: No Answer: 76ers lose again without Iverson
article.story: SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- One night after looking hopelessly sloppy in yet another loss on the road, the Utah Jazz were perfectly crisp back at home. The Jazz shot better than 60 percent through three quarters and cut their turnovers nearly in half from the previous night in a 106-97 win Monday over the Philadelphia 76ers. "We realized that those types of things can't happen every night if we're trying to win ballgames," said Raja Bell, who had 16 points off the bench against his former team. "I think tonight we were a little more focused on not turning it over and really concentrating from the free throw line." The Jazz committed 23 turnovers =tâwere just 17-for-31 from the free-throw line Sunday in a 98-89 loss at Sacramento. On Monday, Utah had just 12 turnovers and went 18-for-22 from the line. "Open looks translate into higher field goal percentages," Bell said. "When you're running helter skelter and you don't know where your shots are coming from, it's a little harder to be focused on knocking shots down." Former Sixer Matt Harpring scored 19 points and reserve point guard Raul Lopez had 13 points and 10 assists. Carlos Arroyo had 19 points and seven assists and Andrei Kirilenko had 1»?/bints, seven rebounds and four blocks for the Jazz, who swept the season series against Philadelphia for the second time in three years. "We let them make shots in the beginning and they got confidence," said Glenn Robinson, who led Philadelphia with 25 points. "It seemed like everything they threw up they made, especially their little guards. They're quick and they're crafty." Utah finished 40-for-72 (56 percent) from the floor and won for the first time when scoring 100 or more points. The Jazz had been 0-3 when topping 100. Eric Snow had 22 points and 10 assists for the Sixers, who were playing their eighth straight game without Allen Iverson (sore knee). PhMdelphia los its third straight and fifth in six games. "You don't beat too many teams that shoot 56 percent on tØÖÉ road. That's the difference," Snow said. Both teams played the night before but didn't show much fatigue offensively. The shorthanded Sixers, who also were without guard Aaron McKie, were 33-for-70 from the floor. Utah was even better, finishing 40-for-72 (56 percent). Harpring, who played for the Sixs in 2001-02 before signing with Utah as a free agent, was 8-for-12. Utah led 56-44 at halftime and never let the Sixers get closer than nine until the final minute, when it was too late. Philadelphia trailed 104-95 when Kenny 4zomas, who scored 11, blocked Bell with 56 seconds to play. Robinson made two free throws to make it 104-97 and the Sixers got a last chance when Bell was called for offensive foul with shot clock winding down. But Thomas missed a layup for Philadelphia, and Bell hit a late jumper as the Sixers backed off defensively to let the clock run out. Utah coach Jerry Sloan was openly critical of his team's lackluster effort the night before. Whatever he said seemed to get through. "If I have to run and feed them a handful of candy after every little thing that goes wrong, they're looking at the wrong guy," Sloan said. "They've got to grow up and learn how to play."< ^Notes@: McKie missed his first game of the season for Philadelphia, hC1wing out with a sore hamstring. ... The Sixers fell to 4-6 without Iverson this season. ... Jazz center Greg Ostertag also missed the game with a sore left knee. He has sat out two of the last three games.
